OL,3,GUK long range forecast
OL,4,
OL,5,COutlook for Mon 27 Apr to Wed 6 May
OL,6,FHigh pressure is likely to remain
OL,7,Fcentred close to or over the UK
OL,8,Fthrough the remainder of April and
OL,9,Finto early May. This means a
OL,10,Fcontinuation of the predominantly dry
OL,11,Fconditions, likely with a mixture of
OL,12,Fsome cloudier spells and sunnier days.
OL,13,FFor the most part, rain-bearing
OL,14,Fweather systems should be kept at bay,
OL,15,Fthough the far west and northwest may
OL,16,Fseeing a little rain at times. Winds
OL,17,Fwill be mostly light, but may be
OL,18,Ffresher around the coasts at times.
OL,19,FFor most, temperatures will continue
OL,20,Fabove normal, though it will feel
OL,21,Fcooler along windward coasts in
OL,22,Fparticular. Towards the end of the
OL,23,QppppppppppppppppppppGSource: Met Office
OL,23,Fperiod, conditions may become more
OL,24,ANext Page  BWeather  CReg News  FReg TV
OL,24,Funsettled as low pressure becomes
OL,25,Frather more dominant.
FL,164,160,301,260,100,100
PN,16303
SC,0003
CT,20,T
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F163A1776867068
OL,1,Wj5hw1~{4k7juhw1{$             G3/3
OL,2,W+.-'"-$/*%*%*%/"-$/*%Q,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,3,GUK long range forecast
OL,4,
OL,5,COutlook for Thu 7 May to Thu 21 MayFA
OL,6,Fgenerally more changeable or unsettled
OL,7,Fspell of weather compared to the
OL,8,Fprevious couple of weeks. This comes
OL,9,Fabout as Atlantic low pressure systems
OL,10,Fmove towards the UK, increasing the
OL,11,Fchance of periods of heavy rain and
OL,12,Fperhaps strong winds at times. Towards
OL,13,Fthe middle of the month, weather
OL,14,Fpatterns become increasingly
OL,15,Funcertain; however, the wettest and
OL,16,Fwindiest conditions seem most likely
OL,17,Fto be in the northwest, with the drier
OL,18,Fand more settled conditions in the
OL,19,Fsoutheast. Temperatures will likely be
OL,20,Fnear or a little above normal overall.
OL,23,QppppppppppppppppppppGSource: Met Office
